In Node.js, the 'fs' (File System) module provides methods for interacting with the file system, including reading and writing files asynchronously. Two of the most commonly used methods are fs.writeFile() and fs.readFile().

○ fs.writeFile():
  o Used to create or overwrite a file with the specified content.
  o Asynchronous and non-blocking, ensuring better performance.
  o If the file does not exist, it is automatically created.
  o Takes three parameters: file path, data to write, and a callback function.
  o Example usage:
    fs.writeFile("example.txt", "Hello, Node.js!", function(err) {
      if (err) throw err;
      console.log("File written successfully.");
    });

○ fs.readFile():
  o Used to read the contents of a file asynchronously.
  o Prevents blocking the execution of other code.
  o Takes three parameters: file path, encoding (optional), and a callback function.
  o Example usage:
    fs.readFile("example.txt", "utf8", function(err, data) {
      if (err) throw err;
      console.log("File contents: " + data);
    });

○ Key Differences:
  o fs.writeFile() is used for writing data to a file, while fs.readFile() is used for reading data.
  o Both methods are asynchronous and require callback functions.
  o fs.readFile() requires an encoding parameter (optional) to return a readable string.

○ Use Cases:
  o fs.writeFile() is used for logging, configuration file updates, or saving user data.
  o fs.readFile() is useful for reading JSON configurations, template files, or logs.

